observations.recommendation:
We recommend that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant the following courses of action:
a) Conduct periodic monitoring, analysis and reconciliation of the funds transferred between the books of the LGU and the recipient agencies, as well as those whose whereabouts could not be determined;
b) Verify and validate the dormant accounts to any available source documents and draw the necessary adjusting the necessary adjusting entry if it was a result of an accounting error, or if warranted, include in the request for write-off;
c) Conduct a comprehensive review, analysis and evaluation of the inactive and non-moving accounts and subsequently submit request for write-off in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
d) Analyze discrepancies noted from confirmations with the IAs and reconcile/adjust accordingly. Also, make representation with the IAs concerned to investigate, verify and reconcile the records on those funds transferred but reported as not received by them and not existing in their books of accounts.

We recommend that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Engineer and the Project Monitoring Committee the following courses of action:

a) To adhere to the requirements prescribed under Section 17.6 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of RA 9184 regarding the conduct of bidding and award for infrastructure contracts;

b) To resolve the issues such as RROW, relocation of informal settlers and viability of the project sites be properly addressed during the feasibility or preliminary engineering study prior to project implementation. These problems should be disclosed during the planning stage and extensively discussed when deliberations for the project’s implementation are conducted with management officials and implementing offices to avoid delay in the implementation of the projects;

c) To thoroughly review and evaluate the Program of Work to ensure that project designs and estimates are properly prepared and that all phases of the projects are covered to minimize variation orders and time extensions which often resulted in the increase of project cost and delayed completion; and

d) To ensure full coordination with other department heads concerned, including the affected community and private utilities, to achieve effective and more synchronized planning of programs and projects.
